- Context:This page defines the mission and core principles of Safe Systems of Work, along with a definition of what constitutes a Safe System of Work.
- Text:4. Our Mission
“To protect people and businesses by delivering practical, audit-ready safe systems of
work and risk control solutions that enable confident operational delivery."
This mission underpins every element of SSoW development and implementation.
5. Core Principles
All Safe Systems of Work developed under this framework are guided by the following
principles:
Safety as Standard
Protecting people is fundamental to every recommendation and system we develop.
Built for the Real World
Documentation must be practical, clear, and usable within live operational
environments.
Compliance Without Complication
Systems must meet regulatory requirements without introducing unnecessary
bureaucracy.
Operational Alignment
SSoW must reflect how work is actually carried out on site.
Audit-Ready by Design
Documentation must be structured, traceable, and aligned with regulatory
expectations.
Clear & Direct Communication
Technical information must be easily understood by those carrying out the work.
6. What is a Safe System of Work?
A Safe System of Work is a formal procedure that defines how work is to be carried out
safely, identifying hazards, assessing risks, and implementing control measures to
reduce risk to an acceptable level.
